---
title: Mediterranean Couscous with Salmon plus Chickpeas, Zucchini & Grape Tomatoes
description: You haven’t tasted chickpeas until you’ve tried them roasted. Trust us, the delicious crunch is absolutely worth the time they spend in a hot oven. In this recipe, they’re roasted with smoked paprika and tossed with bubbly Israeli couscous, roasted zucchini and tomatoes, and feta cheese for a mishmash of savory Mediterranean flavors. You likely won’t have leftovers, but if you do, they’ll taste even better the next day.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/62bc5a59d3552d84c9015faf-980fc6c6.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/mediterranean-couscous-with-salmon-62bc5a59d3552d84c9015faf-3259eb99.pdf
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/mediterranean-couscous-with-salmon-62bc5a59d3552d84c9015faf
author: HelloFresh
cuisine: Mediterranean
servings: 2
time required: 30 minutes
nutrition:
  calories: 990 kcal
  fat: 48 g
  saturated fat: 14 g
  carbohydrates: 89 g
  sugar: 13 g
  protein: 47 g
  fiber: 9 g
  sodium: 930 mg
course: main course
---

Adjust racks to middle and top positions and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Trim and dice @zucchini{1}(trimmed and diced into 1/2-inch pieces). Halve @grape tomatoes{4%oz}. Strip @thyme{1/4%oz} leaves from stems. Peel and mince @garlic{1%clove}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Halve @lemon{1}.

Toss zucchini, tomatoes, and half the thyme leaves on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tbsp}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Roast on middle rack, tossing halfway through, until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Meanwhile, drain and rinse @chickpeas{1%can}; dry thoroughly with #paper towels{}. On a second baking sheet, toss half the chickpeas with a large drizzle of olive oil, @smoked paprika{1%tsp}, and a pinch of salt and pepper.

Roast on top rack, tossing halfway through, until crisp, ~{18-20%minutes}.

> It's natural for the chickpeas to pop a bit while roasting.

While chickpeas roast, heat @butter{1%tbsp} (2 TBSP for 4 servings), garlic, and scallion whites in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat; cook until butter has melted and garlic is fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add @Israeli couscous{3/4%cup} and remaining thyme leaves; stir to coat. Season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring, until couscous is lightly toasted, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @veggie stock concentrate{1} and 3/4 cup water (1 1/2 cups for 4 servings) to pot with couscous. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook until couscous is tender, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Drain any excess liquid if necessary. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While couscous cooks, pat @salmon{10%oz} dry with paper towels; season with salt and pepper. Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a large, preferably #nonstick pan{} over medium-high heat. Cook salmon (skin sides down) until skin is crisp, ~{5-7%minutes}, then flip and cook until cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes} more. Transfer to a #cutting board{}.

Add half the veggies, half the @feta cheese{1/2%cup}, and a squeeze of lemon juice to pot with couscous; stir to combine. Season with salt and pepper.

Divide between plates; top with roasted chickpeas and remaining veggies. Garnish with scallion greens and remaining feta. Serve.

> You likely won't have leftovers, but if you do, they'll taste even better the next day.